## 5. PACKAGE AND DEPENDENCY ISSUES

### 5.1 Hallucinated Packages (Slopsquatting)

**Description:** AI confidently recommends npm packages that do not exist. In ~20% of examined cases (across 576,000 samples), recommended packages didn't exist. Attackers can register these hallucinated package names with malicious code ("slopsquatting").

**Bad code:**
```typescript
import { validateEmail } from 'email-validator-pro'; // Doesn't exist
import { utilityFunction } from 'lodash-advanced'; // Doesn't exist
import { parse } from 'ts-migrate-parser'; // Hallucinated by ChatGPT
```

**Good code:**
```typescript
import validator from 'validator'; // Real, well-known package
import { merge } from 'lodash'; // Real, well-known package
import ts from 'typescript'; // Real, official package
```

**Why AI does this:** "A majority of hallucinations are not just random noise, but repeatable artifacts of how the models respond to certain prompts." Models generate plausible names based on naming conventions.

**Impact:** Supply chain attacks if an attacker registers the hallucinated package name. Build failures. Wasted developer time.

**Detection:** `npm install` will fail for non-existent packages. Verify all packages in npm registry before installation. Use lockfiles. ESLint `import/no-unresolved`.

**Sources:**
- [Slopsquatting: AI Hallucinations and Supply Chain Risk](https://fossa.com/blog/slopsquatting-ai-hallucinations-new-software-supply-chain-risk/)
- [AI Code Tools Widely Hallucinate Packages](https://www.darkreading.com/application-security/ai-code-tools-widely-hallucinate-packages)
- [AI-Hallucinated Code Dependencies](https://www.bleepingcomputer.com/news/security/ai-hallucinated-code-dependencies-become-new-supply-chain-risk/)
- [Package Hallucinations (Snyk)](https://snyk.io/articles/package-hallucinations/)

---

### 5.2 Outdated/Deprecated Library APIs

**Description:** AI training data contains deprecated packages and old API patterns. It recommends libraries that were archived years ago.

**Bad code:**
```typescript
// 'request' was deprecated/archived in 2020
import * as request from 'request';
request.get(url, callback);

// Old Express error handling
app.use((err, req, res, next) => {
  res.status(500).send(err.message); // Leaks error details
});

// moment.js (legacy, 300KB+)
import moment from 'moment';
const date = moment().format('YYYY-MM-DD');
```

**Good code:**
```typescript
// Modern alternatives
const response = await fetch(url);

// Or with error handling
import { ofetch } from 'ofetch';
const data = await ofetch(url);

// date-fns (tree-shakeable, modern)
import { format } from 'date-fns';
const date = format(new Date(), 'yyyy-MM-dd');
```

**Why AI does this:** Training data cutoff and frequency bias. Older libraries appear more frequently in training data.

**Impact:** Known vulnerabilities (CVEs), missing security patches, larger bundle sizes, no maintenance.

**Detection:** `npm audit`. Check package last-published dates (should be recent). `npm outdated`. Dependency scanning in CI.

**Sources:**
- [Debugging AI-Generated Code](https://www.augmentcode.com/guides/debugging-ai-generated-code-8-failure-patterns-and-fixes)

---

### 5.3 Excessive Dependencies

**Description:** AI pulls in heavy dependencies for trivial tasks. A simple to-do list app generated by AI included 2-5 backend dependencies that weren't needed.

**Bad code:**
```typescript
import _ from 'lodash'; // 72KB for one function

const unique = _.uniq(array);
```

**Good code:**
```typescript
const unique = [...new Set(array)];
```

**Why AI does this:** Training data frequently imports popular libraries. AI doesn't evaluate whether a native alternative exists.

**Impact:** Larger bundle size, more attack surface, more maintenance burden, slower builds.

**Detection:** Bundle analysis (webpack-bundle-analyzer). Dependency review. `you-dont-need-lodash` patterns.

